<p>In Czech language, alphabet differs from English by character <code>CH</code>. It is considered as standalone letter, whereas on English, there's no such letter.</p>  <p>This causes troubles when namespace starts on <code>D</code>, <code>C</code> and <code>CH</code> - especially when StyleCop is configured on build server, which has different locale than developers' machines.</p>  <p>(just note, Czech alphabet is: <code>A B C D E F G H CH I J K</code> ...)</p>  <p>According to SA1210, this is correct for <code>en-US</code></p>  <pre><code>using System.ServiceModel.Channels; using System.ServiceModel.Dispatcher; </code></pre>  <p>... but for <code>cs-CZ</code> order should look like this:</p>  <pre><code>using System.ServiceModel.Dispatcher; using System.ServiceModel.Channels; </code></pre>  <p>I found StyleCop configuration element:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;StringProperty Name="Culture"&gt;en-US&lt;/StringProperty&gt; </code></pre>  <p>... unfortunately it does not enforce correct ordering on developer machine with <code>cs-CZ</code> locale. (I'm getting StyleCop error either on developer machine or build server)</p>  <p>Is there any way how to force StyleCop checking ordering in given locale, no matter what system locale is?</p>